1217":"1165–1217","–Female":"Deceased","environ 1224":"about 1224","aproximadamente 1175":"about 1175","aproximadamente 1170":"about 1170","aproximadamente 1217":"about 1217","1165":"1165","environ 1150":"about 1150","1175":"1175","1230":"1230","1262":"1262","1162":"1162","1150":"1150","1182":"1182","1170":"1170","1180":"1180","1217":"1217","1224":"1224","1201":"1201","1222":"1222","1155":"1155","Milano, Lombardy, Italy":"Milan, Lombardy, Italy","Itália":"Italy","Genoa, Genova, Liguria, Italy":"Genoa, Genova, Liguria, Italy","Genova, Liguria, Italia":"Genova, Liguria, Italy","nameMeanings":[{"name":"DORIA","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Italian (mainly <b>Doria</b>):","metronymic from the female personal name <i>Oria</i>, from Latin <i>Aurea</i>, <i>Auria</i> ‘golden’.","habitational name for someone from a place called Oria, of which there are many examples."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Niccolò","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the post-classical Greek personal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Nickolas","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: variant spelling of   Nicholas  , influenced by the short form   Nick ."]},{"name":"Nicolas","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."]}]},{"name":"Ier","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from Yiddish <i>ber</i> ‘bear’, probably influenced by the early medieval European practice of giving animal names to people. It is often paired with   Dov   in order to provide a Hebrew name in certain rituals."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Niccolò Ier DORIA was born about 1150 as the son of Simone Doria and Adelasia T. Zaccaria CASTELLO. He married Giacomettina DELLA VOLTA. They were the parents of at least 4 sons. In 1201, at the age of 52, his occupation is listed as console di genova. He died about 1224, in Italy, at the age of 76."},"et":{"environ 1150–environ 1224":"umbes 1150–umbes 1224","1150–1224":"1150–1224","1155–1224":"1155–1224","1162–1222":"1162–1222","1170–1230":"1170–1230","1175–Male":"1175–Surnud","1180–1262":"1180–1262","1182–Male":"1182–Surnud","1165–1217":"1165–1217","–Female":"Surnud","environ 1224":"umbes 1224","aproximadamente 1175":"umbes 1175","aproximadamente 1170":"umbes 1170","aproximadamente 1217":"umbes 1217","1165":"1165","environ 1150":"umbes 1150","1175":"1175","1230":"1230","1262":"1262","1162":"1162","1150":"1150","1182":"1182","1170":"1170","1180":"1180","1217":"1217","1224":"1224","1201":"1201","1222":"1222","1155":"1155","Milano, Lombardy, Italy":"Milano, Lombardia, Itaalia","Itália":"Itaalia","Genoa, Genova, Liguria, Italy":"Genova, Genova, Liguria, Itaalia","Genova, Liguria, Italia":"Genova, Liguria, Itaalia"},"fi":{"environ 1150–environ 1224":"noin 1150–noin 1224","1150–1224":"1150–1224","1155–1224":"1155–1224","1162–1222":"1162–1222","1170–1230":"1170–1230","1175–Male":"1175–Kuollut","1180–1262":"1180–1262","1182–Male":"1182–Kuollut","1165–1217":"1165–1217","–Female":"Kuollut","environ 1224":"noin 1224","aproximadamente 1175":"noin 1175","aproximadamente 1170